Viewership Data

The table below summarizes the average US viewership (in millions) by season, based on data from the Wikipedia.

Summary Statistics

summary_stats <- gossip_data %>%
  summarise(
    Mean = round(mean(Viewership), 2),
    Max = max(Viewership),
    Min = min(Viewership),
    Season_Max = Season[which.max(Viewership)],
    Season_Min = Season[which.min(Viewership)]
  )

summary_stats
##   Mean  Max  Min Season_Max Season_Min
## 1 1.94 2.81 1.27          2          6

Viewership Trend by Season

ggplot(gossip_data, aes(x = Season, y = Viewership)) +
  geom_line(color = "chocolate4", linewidth = 1.2) +
  geom_point(size = 3, color = "yellow4") +
  labs(
    title = "Average Viewership per Season",
    x = "Season",
    y = "Viewers (Millions)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Season-to-Season Change

gossip_data <- gossip_data %>%
  mutate(Change = c(NA, round(diff(Viewership), 2)))

ggplot(gossip_data[-1, ], aes(x = factor(Season), y = Change)) +
  geom_col(fill = "chocolate4") +
  labs(
    title = "Viewership Change Between Seasons",
    x = "Season",
    y = "Change in Viewership (Millions)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Observations

  • The show peaked in Season 2 with 2.81 million viewers on average.
  • By Season 6, viewership had declined to 1.27 million.
  • Notably, viewership dropped by 0.79 million between Season 2 and 3, which marked a key downturn.
